[normal]1. 
[normal]By their very nature MSLs assessments are seen to be prejudicial to 
[normal]meeting the
[normal] needs of 
[normal]these vulnerable groups 
[normal]who are already at higher risk of isolation, less able to access health and retail services [often including Post Offices and Banks] 
[normal]and there is little, if any, evidence that the
[normal]ir
[normal] needs influence 
[normal]these decisions.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2. 
[normal]However 
[normal]feedback 
[normal]from
[normal] 
[normal]some
[normal] resident
[normal]s 
[normal]shows 
[normal]that there is a ‘cultivated resilience’ based on cycling; walking; ‘cadging a lift’ and ‘friendly taxi services. The qualification is that ‘no pavements’ and ‘no street lighting
[normal]’
[normal] impose restrictions on times of day. It has been pointed out that it 
[normal]also affects visitors.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2. 
[normal]For those reasons
[normal] [2.1.]
[normal] it is imperative that Community Transport 
[normal][CT] 
[normal]initiatives [e.g. encouraging very local ‘Book –A-Ride schemes] are 
[normal]provided
[normal] and
[normal] that
[normal] every opportunity is used to ensure that residents are aware of such services.
[normal] Local Community Transport ‘not – for – profit’ operators should be encouraged to apply for Section 19 &amp; Section 22 permits. The use of concessionary fare 
[normal]passes should be exten
[normal]ded to CT in ‘off route’ localities.
