[normal]3
[normal] [bold]. [bold]What are the main challenges associated with providing better and more consistent bus and rail services [bold]to isolated communities? How can these challenges be o[bold]vercome?[bold]3.1. The Challenges.
[normal]The main challenges are seen to be ensuring that services:
[normal]-  Satisfy residents’ needs;
[normal]-  Are co-ordinated, integrated, and affordable;
[normal]-  Reduce car usage, road congestion; and
[normal] a
[normal]s a consequence decrease in the carbon 
[normal]footprint.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2. The County Council has focused on two primary 
[normal]goals:[bold]• to tackle the growth in car use and consequential increase in congestion; and
[normal]• to improve accessibility to the four key service/amenities of health, employment, education and food sho
[normal]pping for identified socially excluded groups.
[normal]We would prefer the wider definition:- ‘residents in rural areas, especially socially excluded groups’.
[normal]We also see it as essential that 
[normal]there is a 
[normal]commitment to use new technology to provide easily accessible
[normal] ‘Real Time’ reliable, accurate
[normal] travel information covering, and available in, rural areas.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3. From our members’ feedback the personal reasons for using a car are pointedly related to 
[normal]staged journeys[bold] 
[normal][i.e. changes for various parts of the journey]
[normal]   wi
[normal]th dis-satisfaction focused on the inconveniences:
[normal]- the journey, it’s stages / distances 
[normal]t
[normal]imes
[normal] and ticketing
[normal] and, above all reliability
[normal]; 
[normal]- the weather; 
[normal]- having to carry (heavy) items;
[normal]- 
[normal]T
[normal]he walking environment
[normal] /
[normal] 
[normal]availability of 
[normal]safe
[normal] cycling routes
[normal] to bus stops or train stations; and 
[normal]- parking facilities/costs at railway stations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]4
[normal]. Tackling the problems.
[normal]From our review of various Government and other reports dealing with rural services it is seen as essential to:
[normal]- Address the perceived p
[normal]ract
[normal]ical barriers to using public transport;
[normal]              
[normal]- 
[normal]Question the relative costs
[normal] 
[normal]of using the car
[normal]; 
[normal]              
[normal]- Adopt a 
[normal]Door – to- Door [bold]strategy
[normal] based on sustainable transport and integration of services.
[normal]Successful integration is seen to require direct ‘fast’ [express] routes - Rail and Road- that are reliable, 
[normal]and 
[normal]supported by flexible demand responsive services.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.
[normal]5
[normal]. Marketing.
[normal]3.
[normal]5
[normal].1 Levels of interest.
[normal]Local feedback indicates that people plan and make
[normal] their travel decisions based on:
[normal]- Needs, options and experience [level of satisfaction and /or prejudice]; 
[normal]- Information available; information provided including advertising; but
[normal]- Above all on ‘trust’ – i
[normal].e.
[normal] certainty /reliability of delivery and
[normal] easy
[normal] access to real time information
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]when   problems occur e.g. delays, breakdowns and re-routing through road closures / events.
[normal]              
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]5
[normal].2. Generally speaking we have found that the level of knowledge about services is greater for ‘
[normal]captive passengers’
[normal] i.e. 
[normal]people with 
[normal]no practical alternative. For this group they have their 
[normal]own 
[normal]experience
[normal]s
[normal] and share knowledge /enquiry points with and through fellow passengers – the value from “word of mouth”.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The 
[normal]‘choice passengers’
[normal] tend not to consider the alternative to t
[normal]he car, or if they do, find difficulty in accessing relevant information, particularly on links and ticketing. 
[normal]To win them over it will be necessary to design/ publish routes 
[normal]as seamless and as easy as ‘getting in the car’.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]5
[normal].3. A fundamental need is a
[normal] series of coordinated, proactive advertising campaigns with clear definition of routes, links and ticketing arrangements. Part of which has to be ready access to ‘ door-to-door’ information including the ‘park &amp; ride’ options with specific attention to st
[normal]ation car parks!
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]5
[normal].4. The other side of the ‘campaigning’ is to target the car user by presenting real evidence of the cost of using a car and for individuals recognising the time their journeys by car actually take. Other factors are the ability to ‘wo
[normal]rk’ on the journey.
[normal]The downside is the effect on the local economy; Servicing and fuel sales. 
[normal]Compromise
[normal]? Car sharing!
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]5
[normal].5. 
[normal]To 
[normal]develop
[normal] 
[normal]the local economy the potential for targeting / encouraging 
[normal]visitors [bold]warrants active consideration, not only for
[normal] the 
[normal]social contact from 
[normal] visiting relatives b
[normal]ut particularly ‘tourists’ for local 
[normal]attractions
[normal] e.g. scenery and waterways, country walks/ cycle rides and wildlife/ bird sanctuaries. 
