[normal]4.[bold] How[bold] effectively [bold]d[bold]o community transport services address the needs of pass[bold]engers in isolated communities? How can community transport be improved?[bold]4.1. Maldon District Community Transport [‘Viking’] is largely funded by Essex County Council in partnership with Maldon District Council. It is a registered charity and therefore pos
[normal]sible for the Trustee Board to apply for additional grants from other funding sources. Viking runs its services 
[normal]under
[normal] two main headings;
[normal]4.1.1.  Book – A - ride Scheme[bold].
[normal]An annual 
[normal]membership 
[normal]subscription is charged.
[normal] 
[normal]The scheme 
[normal]provides
[normal] a pre-booked, chargea
[normal]ble service that collects a member from their home and takes them t
[normal]o the required destination. Used
[normal] for such things as shopping, visiting friends, social outings, learning opportunities 
[normal]and
[normal] to visit people in hospital. The services are carried out by
[normal] volunteer drivers using their
[normal] own vehicles or by wheelchair accessible minibus.
[normal]The charges are based on a cost per mile with a minimum charge per one-way trip when using volunteers and their vehicles. Where there is no volunteer driver available within a
[normal] reasonable distance of the passengers ‘pick up’ community transport can subsidise each journey. Due to the higher costs of running an accessible minibus a subsidised sliding scale of charges is available on application.
[normal]Every journey must be booked with a
[normal] minimum two working days’ notice and can be block booked for regular journeys - all bookings are dependent on a volunteer driver being available.
[normal]The Scheme is 
[normal]wholly
[normal] dependent on volunteer drivers. 
[normal]4.1.2. Minibus hire scheme.[bold]The scheme enables any bona
[normal] fide non-profit making
[normal] member
[normal] group within the district to hire a minibus. The minibuses have up to 15 passenger seats which can be configured to accommodate wheelchairs.
[normal] 
[normal]Bookings are made on a first-come first-served basis and must be made at least five 
[normal]working days in advance.
[normal] 
[normal]Groups using the service pay an annual subscription. The hiring of a minibus is on a unit cost per mile for the total journey. There is a minimum charge per hire.
[normal]Currently 
[normal]‘
[normal]Viking
[normal]’
[normal] ha
[normal]s
[normal] about 
[normal]90 fully trained MIDAS drivers. All dri
[normal]vers are CRB checked. Some groups have their own 
[normal]registered qualified 
[normal]driver which allows easier planned excursions.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4
[normal].2. 
[normal]Improvements looked for are:
[normal]- Better publicity and proactive community engagement especially for 
[normal]volunteer 
[normal]driver recruitment;
[normal]- 
[normal]More decentralised location of minibuses to reduce dead mileage and improve convenience for drivers;
[normal]- 
[normal] 
[normal]Consideration of service / operational advantages that Section 
[normal]2
[normal]2 Permits bring;
[normal]-  Campaign for concessionary bus passes to be used
[normal] for CT services
[normal] in 
[normal]‘deep rural’ / 
[normal]MSL 
[normal]areas to link with
[normal]   
[normal]Main
[normal] 
[normal]routes [Bus and Rail].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5. [bold]To what exten[bold]t[bold] [bold]should [bold]passengers in isolated communities be expected to rely on tax[bold]i[bold]s and other demand responsive transport services?[bold]5.1. Taxis are often not a real option due to costs. Service providers tend to be based in the ‘busier areas’ with their focus on higher numbers of customers for shorter /regular journeys. Travel vouchers for meeting part of the 
[normal]journey 
[normal]cost where a conces
[normal]sionary fare pass is held are a possible answer to taxi fares but are seen as an ‘administrative nightmare’.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2. 
[normal]Integration of services by 
[normal]DRT links
[normal] [commercial and subsidised]
[normal] to bus and train 
[normal]routes are seen to be the 
[normal]effective 
[normal]way forward.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]6. What [bold]are the main challenges associated with funding transport services in isolated community? How can these services be made more affordable?[bold]6.1. We are in a ‘guess and fear’ stage. To date, for a lay group such as ourselves, information on the cuts, and thei
[normal]r timing, is being released in general terms only. Attempts to get assessment from both local councils and service operators have essentially been dead batted. Everyone it seems is waiting for details. The first challenge is to provide details of subsidy b
[normal]udget changes i.e. for both subsidised commercial services and Community Transport services. At the same time it is essential that the proposals for changes to commercial services are the subject of discussion at the same time.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.2. The broadly held assum
[normal]ption is that we are entering into a less [possibly non-] subsidised era. In some quarters there is a belief that, over and above the CSR, overall bus subsidies could be reduced by up to 50%. The expectation is that the impact from BSOG changes /reductions
[normal] will be heavier in rural areas which are unlikely to be developed as 
[normal]‘
[normal]Better Bus Areas
[normal]’
[normal]. Then there are fuel price rises. 
[normal]The fear in some quarters is that there is also the prospect that the reimbursement for concessionary fare passengers will not be ‘i
[normal]nflation proofed’.  If this were to be true it will almost inevitably mean that there will be a freezing of, if not reduction in, mainstream bus services. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.3. 
[normal]There is general, if reluctant, a
[normal]ccept
[normal]ance
[normal] that the budget changes driven by the need to reduc
[normal]e public expenditure will inevitably mean that funding will decline and reinforce the need for efficiency in the design/delivery of services. 
[normal]That
[normal] should also mean 
[normal]all
[normal] services/budgets are reviewed to ensure they 
[normal]each
[normal] provide the best match against social 
[normal]needs. In turn that requires a move from ‘Post graduate mathematics’ to meaningful communication; paying less attention to 
[normal]what[bold] we spend, rather put the emphasis on 
[normal]how[bold] we spend it.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.4. Our
[normal] experiences
[normal] lead us to believe that even without the budget redu
[normal]ctions the ‘Big Society’ proposals provide th
[normal]e
[normal] opportunity to think laterally– to focus on local transport needs and tailor facilities to match those needs in the context of both the economy and the environment. With meaningful community engagement i.e. In
[normal]volvement* allowing agreement on local priorities
[normal],
[normal] these strategies ar
[normal]e seen as a sound framework for 
[normal]action[bold].
[normal]* I.e. 
[normal]the step 
[normal]beyond consultation [This is what we are going to do –what do you think?]; past partic
[normal]ipation [
[normal]this is what we are going to do how
[normal] can it be done?] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.5. Fares versus public funding.
[normal]6.5.1. 
[normal]The 
[normal]C
[normal]ommunity 
[normal]T
[normal]ransport sector 
[normal]needs
[normal] 
[normal]to be 
[normal]a significant player in the market 
[normal]given cost advantages following from
[normal] the 
[normal]volunt
[normal]eer ‘work force’ 
[normal]accepting
[normal] roles as drivers, passenger assistan
[normal]ts
[normal], and
[normal] admin staff
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]essentially 
[normal]invest
[normal]ment
[normal] ‘in kind’ i.e. 
[normal]their 
[normal]time
[normal] and skills
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.5.2. 
[normal]It is seen as essential in planning public transport that education
[normal] and
[normal] health
[normal] authorities think about transport beyond the statutory deliverables. Local partnerships will need to include
[normal] 
[normal]in the
[normal]ir
[normal] deliberations 
[normal]education planning and hospital transport
[normal], including moving staff and patients
[normal] between hospitals
[normal]. This also covers the need
[normal] to ensure fair and equitable access to extending school provision – breakfast and after-school club events. This planning is seen to be particularly important with the reduction/withdrawal of education maintenance allowance
[normal] and the features attached to th
[normal]e extension of school leaving age
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.5.3. 
[normal]Significantly the 
[normal]largely (
[normal]85% by mileage
[normal]) commercially operated bus network will, by its 
[normal]very 
[normal]nature, be
[normal] 
[normal]subject to commercial pressures and changes.
[normal] 
[normal]With any level of service reduction the impact is likely to be
[normal] serious at this time when both customers [passengers] and contractors need usage to rise in order to maintain, let alone improve, service levels.
[normal] Our view is that there is an urgent need for voluntary and community sector groups working in partnership wi
[normal]th the local contractors, to design and provide more rational, integrated and relevant facilities. However, without access to facts it is impossible to even start pulling together a meaningful business plan. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.6. Policies.
[normal]6.6.1. A basic rule of Manageme
[normal]nt is that “
[normal]Plans should be Strategy led and Resource disciplined
[normal]” and therein lies a [the] major challenge. Both Essex County Council and Maldon District Council have published detailed Strategic Plans in the past but both expired in 2011 and have yet to 
[normal]be updated / replaced. Whilst the content gave a clear view of what was looked for, the steps to achieve them were not always clear. The reality check for plans made by all levels of Government is that although budgets have been set, the spending will be s
[normal]ubject to political choice – possibly well illustrated by current debate over HS2. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.6.2. Again in Management terms it is not only necessary to decide 
[normal]What[bold] it is you want to happen but decide 
[normal]How [bold]to make it happen. This presents a further challenge 
[normal]when
[normal] 
[normal]deciding authority / accountability. All too often the bureaucracy gets in the way to delay action/ delivery and increase costs – should it really take over two years to put in place a bus stop to reduce risk of injury to people alighting from a bus? It ha
[normal]s in Burnham! 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.7. Looking Forward.
[normal]6.7.1. Central Government has given a clear lead with the Strategies ‘
[normal]Making transport more accessible to all’
[normal] and 
[normal]‘
[normal]Door to door’
[normal] , 
[normal]recommending
[normal] activity concentrating on 4 core areas:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.8. “Liaison is the Key”[bold]6.8.1. Provided the ‘Localism’ [
[normal]see para 6.4.]
[normal] approach is adopted then we have 
[normal]every reason to think that the challenges can be met through active community engagement. This will require ‘
[normal]Partnership Working’
[normal] with the 
[normal]‘Policy People’
[normal] debating the practicalities of delivery with 
[normal]‘Operational Managers’
[normal] as part of their planning process
[normal] and involve service managers and staff in setting standards and measuring them.
[normal]ECC already work closely with bus service users, as ’critical friends’, and service providers to improve transport services –that will need to be the platform for making best 
[normal]use of available resources. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.9. Options.
[normal]6.9.1. Commercial bus operators have several options, they can: 
[normal]- 
[normal]Raise fares - 
[normal]in rural areas such as ours it is felt that current competitive pressures are insufficient to 
[normal]   establish
[normal] a meaningful ‘best value’ test; 
[normal]- 
[normal]Reduce service levels – local experience is that it is all too easy to simply cut out part of the route 
[normal]   effectively to choo
[normal]se the most rewarding locations;
[normal]- Tactical reductions in service frequency, operating hours 
[normal]or days can create savings for operators.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.9.2. Overall our expectation is that low utilisation bus services will be cut and the number of subsidised routes reduced.
[normal] We see it as essential that priority is given to the needs of most vulnerable groups wh
[normal]ere service reductions are proposed and the expectation would be that ECC would find a contractor
[normal] 
[normal]to provide supported journeys
[normal] – in doing so there is the opportunity to adopt DRT links to main services
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.9.
[normal]3
[normal]. Railway Companies’ fares are inflation rela
[normal]ted so the issues for rail travel are somewhat different i.e. tend to be geared to/aligned with customer demand. If a 
[normal]rail 
[normal]company were to hit financial problems they could hand back the franchise and the Government would 
[normal]be likely to 
[normal]step in to ensure 
[normal]continuity of the service before re-letting the franchise with much the same
[normal] 
[normal]service specification as before [e.g. East Coast mainline].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.
[normal]9.
[normal]4
[normal].
[normal] A probable consequence of LA budget cuts [including Community Transport funding] will be that
[normal] Publicly Supporte
[normal]d Bus services
[normal] 
[normal]are removed, reduced, or the network altered.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.
[normal]9.
[normal]5
[normal]. To avoid some ‘no 
[normal]commercial 
[normal]service’ situation
[normal]s
[normal], customer expectation of fares may well need to change. So that affordable fares can be offered, the emphasis will need to be on 
[normal]encouragi[bold]ng more paying customers[bold] [“greater passenger contribution”] and that will require more convenient services i.e. fit for purpose.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.
[normal]9.
[normal]6
[normal].
[normal] County Councils 
[normal]need to 
[normal]plan on the basis of:
