[normal]Participation.[bold]A number of the Committee /members have been involved in an Essex County Council Task and Finish Group involved in the design and introduction the Dengie
[normal] Dart 99 a ‘Dial and Ride’ service from the Dengie to Hospitals and preparing the ground for renewal of local contracts for supported services.  As a result of which some now include DRT elements. Several of our members also serve as Parish Council Transpo
[normal]rt Representatives.
[normal]Our Area: The Dengie.[bold]The Dengie Peninsula is part of the Maldon District in ‘Central Essex’. The peninsula covers an area of about 140 square miles. It is surrounded by water; to the east by the North Sea; to the north by the River Bla
[normal]ckwater; to the south by the River Crouch. There are no bridges across the estuaries, the lowest crossing points on Maldon [Blackwater] and Battlesbridge [Crouch]. The three main centres of population are Burnham on Crouch, Southminster, and Mayland. The p
[normal]eninsula has two of the least densely occupied electoral wards in Essex – Tillingham and St Lawrence.
[normal]The ‘Pensioner Population’ is projected to continue to grow. Against an overall population growth of 5% between 2010 and 2015 the prediction is that the ‘
[normal]over 65s’ will increase by 23% and account for 22% of the population: whilst the ‘over 80s’ will show a 17% increase to about 5% of the total. Feedback shows that generally as they get older people look to drive less, but with infrequent ‘unreliable’ 
[normal]publi
[normal]c transport 
[normal]services find they still need to drive themselves even 
[normal]though 
[normal]they feel unhappy about doing so!
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]For the District as a whole it is reported that 93% of the 25,000 households have at least one car and 15% of these have two or more [3348 househol
[normal]ds]. When a car is used for work the remainder of the house
[normal]hold
[normal] will often be dependent on other means of transport. 69% of economically active residents use 
[normal]a car
[normal] to travel to work, either as drivers or passengers. 9% use public transport [7% train; 2% bu
[normal]s]. 13% cycle or walk. About half the workforce travel out of the district by train or bus and 78% 
[normal]of those 
[normal]by car
[normal] for at least part of the journey
[normal]. These figures illustrate dependence
[normal] of people
[normal] in the area on private transport
[normal] and the potential for change
[normal].
